<div class="comhead" id="dn16911-81">
	
		<h3>Well Is It Or Not?</h3>
		<p class="infotext lowlight">Fri Apr 10 13:16:24 BST 2009 by <b>anonymous</b>
		
		</p>
	
</div>

<div class="combody">
	
	
		<p>What the heck is all this hand-wringing over the "light-source" direction supposed to prove???<br /><br />That picture OBVIOUSLY was taken to keep the light source information as ambiguous as possible. Most likely, it was taken under the equivalent of a "screen light" which would help reduce cues that would give away the effect.<br /><br /> There is no specific "direction" from which the light source is coming from in this image, and anybody who talks about seeing one here couldn't tell the direction of illumination responsible for the difference between a full moon and a half moon.<br /><br /> When you see a bit of "shading" under the chin, say, it does NOT mean that the light is directed from the top! It CAN mean that the surface of the object which is being illuminated from the front exhibits the equivalent of "limb darkening", or more likely in this case, the light source is slightly higher than the camera is but way behind the camera arranged in such a way that the camera itself doesn't cast a shadow onto the target. In this case, it's obvious that it isn't a spot source of light at all, but a significantly wide source such as photographers often employ to suppress topological feature shadows on the subject.<br /><br /> As far as whether its concave or convex, NOBODY can tell. That's the whole point. This direct-on image is completely neutral in terms of information that could be used to determine whether its facing in or out. Any attempt to draw inferences from some light-source cues that simply aren't there is just about as dilapidated as a schizophrenic's view. (And THAT may explain alot in terms of why so many adhere to irrational beliefs, including those of a religious natiure)<br /><br />As for the notion that schizophrenics are able to correctly judge the orientation of such a mask better than non-schizophrenics, I am moved to observe few things: First, I've known a number of schizophrenics who would regard being exposed to such an apparition as the face of the culprit responsible for giving them such a hard time looking in on them (many schizophrenics are extremely paranoid, and would get freaked up just thinking about whether a face can be convex or concave); Second, since the researchers (PRESUMABLY, HOPEFULLY) endeavored to make sure that their set-up was as AMBIGUOUS as possible (yes, including in terms of light sources) their results could simply reflect the difference between ordinary perception - seeing a normal convex face, WHETHER OR NOT IT IS CONVEX OR NOT and the tendency of schizophrenics who have been instructed to report whether the face they are seeing is convex OR concave...<br /><br /> It just may be that this study is full of balloney.</p>
	
</div>

