</div>

<div class="combody">
	
	
		<p>David, thanks for looking up the source article and clarifying that. Beforehand, I could not make sense of what the narrator of the video meant when she said one picture was normal and the other inverted. They were treated in the video as independent 2D images.<br /><br /> I have been into stereophotography for over 20 years now. On a whim and before reading your comment, I looked at the images of the woman as a stereo pair, left and right as presented (left eye on left picture, right eye on right picture). To me it looks like a normal stereo pair of a convex face, albeit with very little parallax (lenses situated closer together than human eyes are spaced) so as to reduce the 3D effect.<br /><br /> As a second check, I viewed the pair cross-eyed, ie, left eye on right picture and right eye on left picture. Sure enough, the face does not look right that way. It no longer looks convex, and it's not flat, as it would look if the pictures were identical. With the reduced parallax, the face is not blatantly concave when inverted, but some things such as the woman's collar are more telling, as it has more depth and definition than much of her face. Also, when inverted, that little tuft of hair or whatever might be behind her collar comes to the apparent "front" in the inverted view<br /><br />Clearly, when the narrator used the word "inverted," she meant - whether she knew it or not - that the left and right pictures were reversed, not that a given, single picture had been "inverted."<br /><br />I would emphasize to those who are not familiar with pictures paired for 3D, they are not identical. They may look similar, but they have been taken from two different locations. It is by comparing the slightly different views that our brains can interpret the 3D effect, thereby providing us information about depth, distance, shape, etc.<br /><br /> If you already understand this, bravo. Enough people, however, have never thought of the basics if binocular vision, and when I share my 3D pictures with people, I often have explain this.<br /><br /> Anyway, obviously the video did a very poor job of explaining the pictures and how they were used. Too bad. Should I assume I'm schizophrenic since I can see the difference betwixt normal and inverted views of THEIR sample pair? I presume what they mean is that schizophrenics have a keener sense of these things for whatever reason, and my best guess is that I'm among that one percent of "normal" people who can tell the difference. Then again, I never claimed to be normal, and I do have a leg up on the subject with my photography hobby.<br /><br /> Food for thought: what about all those 3D films we see at the cinema? Are all of us who can interpret them correctly and see the creature from the black lagoon swimming toward us schizophrenic? Oh, right, it's when the effect is slight that only the schizophrenics can tell the difference. Since camera spacing has infinite variability within its range, where exactly is the cutoff? 2 cm? 1 cm? 3.14 degrees of parallax?<br /><br />Gotta go. There are some nice young men with their clean white coats and they're coming to take me away haha...</p>
	
</div>

